  "market_context": "Analyst walks through a EUR/USD 4-hour chart during a ranging to bearish transition, identifying swing highs/lows as liquidity pools. Focus is on old highs/lows and equal highs/lows, with price sequentially sweeping sell-side then buy-side liquidity.",
  "key_observation": "Price systematically takes out swing lows (sell-side liquidity) and swing highs (buy-side liquidity), with new swing points forming after each sweep, creating sequential liquidity targets.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Define swing low as a low with higher lows on both sides, and swing high as a high with lower highs on both sides, explaining their role as stop-loss clusters.",
    "Step 2: On the 4-hour chart, identify the first obvious swing low at ~1.05238 as sell-side liquidity and a swing high at ~1.06900 as buy-side liquidity.",
    "Step 3: Observe price taking out the initial sell-side liquidity (swing low), then forming a new swing high, which becomes the next buy-side liquidity target.",
    "Step 4: Note that after the first high is taken out, a new lower high forms, establishing fresh buy-side liquidity; price then sweeps that level too.",
    "Step 5: Identify equal lows (relatively equal swing lows not yet taken) as combined sell-side liquidity, and anticipate price targeting them next.",
    "Step 6: Highlight how new swing points form after each liquidity sweep, and how the analyst updates liquidity labels accordingly (e.g., new buyside liquidity at 1.07000–1.07150, sellside at 1.06500–1.06650)."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Swing points define where liquidity rests; price tends to sweep them sequentially. After a liquidity sweep, the former swing point often becomes irrelevant, and new swing points form—requiring dynamic re-labeling of liquidity zones for accurate trade planning.",
